	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Efforts under way to consolidate growth in Kenyan dairy sector </h1>

			
			<h4>
												23 September 2013
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>A report released by the Kenya Dairy Board (KDB) and published in August 2013 shows that the dairy industry in Kenya is primarily smallholder based (70% of milk supply), and that the dairy sector accounts for 14% of Kenya’s agricultural GDP. Liberalisation of the sector since 1992 has seen the emergence of private sector competition for the state-owned Kenya Cooperative Creameries. However, the dairy sector remains strongly affected by seasonal variations and is vulnerable to poor rains and bad grazing.&nbsp; This gives rise to considerable price volatility.</p><p>A lack of investment in storage and long-life milk processing capacity has been identified, with this giving rise to considerable wastage of milk during peak production times. According to the KDB, only 30% of milk produced is processed in factories: most is either consumed locally or sold by street vendors who buy direct from farmers. To address the lack of investment and price volatility, KDB has been seeking to expand the processing and storage facilities of the Kenya Cooperative Creameries.</p><p>There is growing demand for dairy products in Kenya, given the growing population, increasing urbanisation and an emerging middle class. KDB has proposed the creation of a Dairy Development Fund to finance marketing and product development programmes. &nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>In February 2013, a special dairy task force of industry stakeholders was created by the Ministry of Livestock to gather data on supply and demand for dairy products, and to make recommendations on how to manage milk production and demand in the short, medium and long term.&nbsp;</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p><i>Business Daily Africa</i>, ‘Challenges persist despite reforms in the dairy sector’, 8 August 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.businessdailyafrica.com/Challenges+persist+despite+reforms+in+the+dairy+sector/-/539546/1941678/-/d4gh97/-/index.html" target="_self">http://www.businessdailyafrica.com/Challenges+persist+despite+reforms+in...</a></p><p>Kenya Dairy Board, ‘Inauguration of the dairy task force which was held on 20 February 2013’, undated</p><p>
<a href="http://www.kdb.co.ke/index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=224:inauguration-of-the-dairy-task-force-which-was-held-on-20th-february-2013&amp;catid=30:kdb-latest-news" target="_self">http://www.kdb.co.ke/index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;i...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Expanding consumer demand for dairy products is generating growing interest in the East African dairy sector (see <i>Agritrade</i> interview, ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Dairy/A-Danish-perspective-on-investment-in-African-dairy-sector-development" target="_blank">A Danish perspective on investment in African dairy sector development</a>’, 24 February 2013). Although Kenyan production is expanding, variable supply and certain speciality needs require continued imports from the EU and New Zealand to meet market demand.</p><p>It can be argued that the KDB should concentrate on improving the overall policy and business environment to create a level playing field for all actors and attract more private sector investment. This could include the setting up of more collection points closer to small producers. These could then be run by efficient private sector operators, with government supporting targeted road improvements to enhance the accessibility of collection points and cold stores to smallholder producers.</p><p>Initiatives are also required to get to grips with reducing feed costs. This can be seen as essential for improving feed use, increasing milk yields, and making milk supply more regular. The KDB is also likely to face a challenging task in establishing an appropriate regulatory framework for milk standards and in elaborating a dairy sector trade policy that reconciles the interests of different stakeholders (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Dairy/Initiatives-to-establish-an-EAC-regional-dairy-development-strategy" target="_blank">Initiatives to establish an EAC regional dairy development strategy</a>’, 06 October 2011).</p><p>In this context it needs to be recognised that efforts to promote increased commercial processing of dairy products can squeeze out current informal suppliers, who currently account for the bulk of milk supplies to poor households. Such a situation could potentially see poor consumers facing higher prices, and therefore reducing their milk consumption. The issue of the accessibility of milk to the poor recently came to the fore when the government proposed to levy VAT on milk.</p><p>In terms of trade policy, a critical issue will be how to effectively integrate milk powder imports into local dairy value chains in such a way that they:</p>
<ul>

<li>create more employment through local value addition; </li>

<li>benefit consumers by making supplies more regular and reducing price volatility; </li>

<li>benefit producers by supporting improved economies of scale in production and more efficient local milk supply chains. </li>

</ul>
<p>Care will need to be taken to ensure that smallholder producers are not slowly edged out of the domestic market as a result of the promotion of globally integrated dairy product supply chains, which increase pressure on local milk prices.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
	</article>

